'''Fluxus''' is a [[live coding]] environment for 3D graphics, music and games.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fluxus official website|url=http://www.pawfal.org/fluxus/|accessdate=21 August 2012}}</ref> It uses the programming language [[Racket (programming language)|Racket]] (a dialect of [[Scheme (programming language)|Scheme]]/[[Lisp (programming language)|Lisp]]) to work with a games engine with built-in 3D graphics, physics simulation and sound synthesis.  All programming is done on-the-fly, where the code editor appears on top of the graphics that the code is generating.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Magnusson|first=Thor|date=2014-03|title=Herding Cats: Observing Live Coding in the Wild|url=https://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/abs/10.1162/COMJ_a_00216|journal=Computer Music Journal|language=en|volume=38|issue=1|pages=8–16|doi=10.1162/comj_a_00216|issn=0148-9267}}</ref><ref>Wakefield, Graham, Charlie Roberts, Matthew Wright, Timothy Wood and Karl Yerkes. “Collaborative Live-Coding with an Immersive Instrument.” NIME (2014).</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bovermann|first=Till|last2=Griffiths|first2=Dave|date=2014-03|title=Computation as Material in Live Coding|url=https://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/abs/10.1162/COMJ_a_00228|journal=Computer Music Journal|language=en|volume=38|issue=1|pages=40–53|doi=10.1162/comj_a_00228|issn=0148-9267}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deutschlandfunk.de/live-coding-naeher-an-der-musik.807.de.html?dram:article_id=388587|title=Live Coding - Näher an der Musik|work=Deutschlandfunk|access-date=2018-08-21|language=de-DE}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Magnusson|first=Thor|date=2011-12|title=Algorithms as Scores: Coding Live Music|url=https://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/abs/10.1162/LMJ_a_00056|journal=Leonardo Music Journal|language=en|volume=21|issue=21|pages=19–23|doi=10.1162/lmj_a_00056|issn=0961-1215}}</ref>  It is an important reference for research and practice in exploratory programming, pedagogy,<ref>Martins, S. B. (2010). Revisiting the architecture curriculum - the programming perspective. In FUTURE CITIES, 28th eCAADe Conference Proceedings, ETH Zurich (Switzerland).</ref> live performance<ref name="collins" /> and games programming.

Fluxus is known for hosting some of the most cutting-edge live coding research systems <ref name="collins">Collins, N. (2011). [http://www.sussex.ac.uk/Users/nc81/research/livecodingofconsequence.pdf Live coding of consequence]. Leonardo, 44(3):207-211.</ref> by its author Dave Griffiths, such as the BetaBlocker language inspired by [[Core War]], the Al-Jazari music environment based on interacting robots, the Daisy Chain music environment based on the [[Petri net]] model of computation, and the SchemeBricks visual interface for Scheme.<ref>McLean, A., Griffiths, D., Collins, N., and Wiggins, G. (2010). [http://yaxu.org/writing/visualisation-of-live-code.pdf Visualisation of live code]. In Proceedings of Electronic Visualisation and the Arts London 2010.</ref>

